01:17.440 --> 01:19.000
HOWARD:
<i><font size="24"><font face="Arial">Is anybody down there{\r}?</font></font></i>

01:19.000 --> 01:21.000
MARION:
<i><font size="24"><font face="Arial">Just me-- the boys
have left already{\r}.</font></font></i>

01:21.000 --> 01:23.370
<i><font size="24"><font face="Arial">Their band is playing
at a bar mitzvah{\r}.</font></font></i>

01:24.750 --> 01:26.250
Oh...

01:31.260 --> 01:34.260
(no audio)

01:34.760 --> 01:36.260
(singing)
All right,
cut it out, Marion.

01:36.260 --> 01:37.210
Oh, you're
going to be

01:37.760 --> 01:39.180
the cutest chaperone
at the prom.

01:39.180 --> 01:43.520
I asked you to rent me
just a plain, black tuxedo.

01:43.520 --> 01:45.890
Well, black is
out, Howard.

01:45.890 --> 01:47.770
This is hep... I
mean, it's spiffy,

01:47.770 --> 01:49.640
snazzy, gives
you pizzazz.

01:49.640 --> 01:50.610
You really think so?

01:50.610 --> 01:53.110
Pizzazz? Hmm.

01:54.110 --> 01:57.620
Ooh... nice
tuxedo, Dad.

01:58.120 --> 01:58.990
Here it comes.

01:58.990 --> 02:00.320
Did it come with batteries?

02:04.410 --> 02:06.410
Why didn't you put
the address in your wallet?

02:06.410 --> 02:08.410
Because I always lose things
in my wallet.

02:08.410 --> 02:10.410
That's why I put it
in my glove compartment.

02:10.410 --> 02:12.920
It's hard to lose
a glove compartment.

02:12.920 --> 02:14.380
Hey, Howie...

02:14.380 --> 02:15.720
nice tuxedo.

02:15.720 --> 02:18.050
(Ralph chuckling)

02:18.050 --> 02:19.470
Is he gonna be
a chaperone,

02:19.470 --> 02:20.970
or are they hanging
him from the middle

02:20.970 --> 02:22.260
of the gym and
spinning him?

02:23.060 --> 02:24.390
I'm going to spin <i><font size="24"><font face="Arial">you{\r}.</font></font></i>

02:24.390 --> 02:26.010
No, no, no, Dad,
please, please don't.

02:26.010 --> 02:28.850
I'm going upstairs
and take off this neon suit.

02:28.850 --> 02:31.350
Oh, Joanie, go up and tell
him how nice he looks.

02:31.850 --> 02:32.850
It looks great, Dad.

02:32.850 --> 02:35.360
Jenny Piccalo has a
nightgown just like it.

02:35.360 --> 02:36.860
I don't want you

02:36.860 --> 02:39.110
hanging around
that Jenny Piccalo.

02:39.110 --> 02:41.360
She's a 15-year-old
Mae West!

02:41.360 --> 02:42.860
How are we supposed
to play a bar mitzvah

02:43.360 --> 02:44.860
when we don't even know
where it is?

02:44.860 --> 02:46.870
Boys, why don't you just go out

02:46.870 --> 02:49.370
and get the address out
of Ralph's glove compartment?

02:49.370 --> 02:52.370
Because his car is locked
in Fonzie's garage.

02:52.370 --> 02:53.370
Oh, dear.

02:53.370 --> 02:54.870
And we can't
find Fonzie

02:54.870 --> 02:56.380
because it's Friday.

02:56.380 --> 02:57.880
Every Monday, Wednesday,
and Friday night,

02:58.380 --> 03:00.180
Fonzie meets
with some mystery lady.

03:00.180 --> 03:01.850
Now, come on, Ralph.

03:01.850 --> 03:03.220
You wrote the name down.

03:03.220 --> 03:05.220
You must be able to
remember where it is.

03:05.220 --> 03:06.220
I got it!
Good!

03:06.220 --> 03:07.640
RICHIE:
Oh, good,
I knew he'd get it.

03:07.640 --> 03:10.520
I remember that the place
has a girl's name in it.

03:10.520 --> 03:12.030
I told you I'd remember.

03:12.030 --> 03:14.030
Good, good, that...
that's good,

03:14.030 --> 03:17.030
we'll look it up
in the phone book.
All right, great.

03:19.400 --> 03:20.730
What are we gonna do,
look for every place

03:21.230 --> 03:22.240
that has
a girl's name in it?

03:22.240 --> 03:23.740
Yeah.
We'll never find it!

03:23.740 --> 03:25.740
That's hopeless,
my whole life is hopeless!

03:26.240 --> 03:27.120
Yeah, we know
that, Ralph.

03:29.380 --> 03:31.710
Oh, God doesn't want me
to go to the prom.

03:32.210 --> 03:34.080
Oh, Ralph, it will
be all right.

03:34.080 --> 03:35.420
When Fonzie comes
home at 9:30,

03:35.970 --> 03:37.250
he'll open
the garage.

03:37.250 --> 03:38.470
Oh, no, no, Mom,
9:30's gonna be

03:38.470 --> 03:39.920
much too late,
we've got to...

03:42.590 --> 03:45.390
Mom... how do you know

03:45.390 --> 03:46.810
what time Fonzie's
coming home?

03:47.730 --> 03:49.900
You know, boys, I've
been wondering

03:49.900 --> 03:52.400
where you've decided
to go to college.

03:52.400 --> 03:53.900
Oh, Ralph,
you look so nice.

03:53.900 --> 03:55.400
Thank you,
thank you, Mrs. C.

03:55.400 --> 03:56.900
Mom...
Doesn't he?

03:56.900 --> 03:58.400
Mom... how do you know

03:58.400 --> 04:00.410
Fonzie's coming home
at 9:30?

04:00.410 --> 04:01.910
Oh, did I...
did I actually say that?

04:01.910 --> 04:02.910
Yes.
I wasn't...
RALPH:
Mrs. C?

04:02.910 --> 04:03.910
Yes, Ralph, what, dear?

04:03.910 --> 04:04.910
Uh, Mrs. C., um,

04:04.910 --> 04:06.910
nobody knows where
Fonzie's been hanging out

04:06.910 --> 04:08.280
for the last couple
of months-- nobody.

04:08.280 --> 04:10.170
Oh, that's right, so
how would I know?

04:10.170 --> 04:12.170
You didn't pull
9:30 out of a hat.

04:12.170 --> 04:13.670
Oh, just a guess,
just a wild guess,

04:13.670 --> 04:15.170
and not a bad...
good guess at all,

04:15.170 --> 04:17.120
kind of a bad guess,
not a hat-- oh...

04:17.120 --> 04:19.010
Mrs. C., why don't you
just sit down?

04:19.010 --> 04:20.459
All right, thank you.

04:20.459 --> 04:22.960
We need information,
and we need it now.

04:23.460 --> 04:24.960
Oh, Ralph,

04:24.960 --> 04:26.470
this is my mother you're
talking to, you know?

04:26.470 --> 04:29.470
All right,
excuse me, Mrs. C.

04:29.470 --> 04:31.800
Look, Rich, we'll just try
to scare her a little.

04:33.140 --> 04:34.520
You know, you better
stay out of it.

04:34.520 --> 04:36.530
You're too close, okay?

04:36.530 --> 04:38.530
All right, Mrs. C.

04:38.530 --> 04:40.530
Now, you know you're
like a mother to us.

04:40.530 --> 04:41.400
Yes, Ralph.

04:41.400 --> 04:42.730
But, you're not leaving
this room

04:42.730 --> 04:44.120
until you tell us
where Fonzie is.

04:44.120 --> 04:45.450
Right, and we mean business!

04:45.450 --> 04:46.450
All right,
start talking.

04:46.450 --> 04:47.950
Boys, I don't like
being treated this way.

04:48.450 --> 04:49.740
Richard, they are
threatening me.

04:49.740 --> 04:51.320
I can't help you,
Mom, I'm too close.

04:51.320 --> 04:53.130
You're not that close,
Rich-- come on, break her.

04:53.130 --> 04:55.080
All right, all right,
all right, now, Mom?

04:55.080 --> 04:57.580
This is on
your head now.

04:58.080 --> 04:59.470
No bar mitzvah.

05:00.800 --> 05:02.750
And, Mom, we're not gonna
have any money

05:02.750 --> 05:04.250
to go to our senior prom,

05:04.250 --> 05:05.760
our one and only
senior prom.

05:06.260 --> 05:07.260
No prom.
All right.

05:07.260 --> 05:08.760
No girls.
All right,
I'll tell you.

05:08.760 --> 05:10.760
Yeah?
I can't tell you.

05:10.760 --> 05:12.680
(boys groaning)
I promised-- oh, Ralph, please!

05:12.680 --> 05:14.150
Think of the name
of the club.

05:14.150 --> 05:15.100
Don't hit me, Mrs. C.!

05:15.100 --> 05:16.400
Help me, Rich, help!
Oh, Ralph,

05:16.400 --> 05:18.270
dear, I'm so sorry, dear.

05:18.770 --> 05:20.270
It's... it's just
the pressure.

05:20.270 --> 05:22.770
All right,
I'll tell you,

05:22.770 --> 05:25.240
but you have got to promise
that you won't tell a soul.

05:25.240 --> 05:27.280
Oh, we promise, not
a soul, Mrs. C.
Sure, never,
we won't tell anyone.

05:27.280 --> 05:28.780
Fonzie has been...

05:28.780 --> 05:29.700
Yeah, yeah?
Yeah, yeah?
He's at...

05:29.700 --> 05:31.660
Jefferson High School-- there.

05:31.660 --> 05:32.670
RICHIE:
Jefferson?
I've said it.

05:32.670 --> 05:35.170
I've said it.

05:35.170 --> 05:38.420
He's been going to night school.

05:38.420 --> 05:40.790
Boy, did she spill
her guts.

05:46.460 --> 05:47.430
WOMAN:
<i><font size="24"><font face="Arial">Mr. Fonzarelli{\r},</font></font></i>

05:47.430 --> 05:49.720
please recite tonight's poem.

05:49.720 --> 05:51.600
Sure, I'll read
this one, you know,

05:51.600 --> 05:55.610
just for, uh, Michelle
here, all right.
(giggling)

05:56.110 --> 06:00.610
"I Love You"
by Ella Wheeler Wilcox.

06:00.610 --> 06:01.610
(giggling)

06:01.610 --> 06:04.110
Thanks very much,
Michelle.

06:04.110 --> 06:09.120
"I love your lips
when they're wet with wine

06:09.120 --> 06:11.990
and red
with wild desire."

06:11.990 --> 06:13.910
Uh, please, uh, read that again,

06:14.410 --> 06:17.290
and tell me, what does
that line mean to you?

06:20.630 --> 06:23.630
Whoa!

06:24.580 --> 06:26.840
Good, you understand.

06:28.970 --> 06:32.260
FONZIE:
"I love your eyes
when the love light

06:32.260 --> 06:36.260
lies lit with a
passionate fire."

06:36.260 --> 06:37.260
Huh, dig it, whoa.

06:37.760 --> 06:39.730
"I love your arms

06:39.730 --> 06:42.690
"when the warm,
white flesh

06:42.690 --> 06:45.190
touches mine
in a fond embrace."

06:45.190 --> 06:45.990
Whoa.

06:46.940 --> 06:50.580
"I love your hair
when the strands

06:50.580 --> 06:55.580
enmesh and your kisses
against my face", Michelle.

06:55.580 --> 06:58.620
(sighs passionately)
Yeah.

07:00.870 --> 07:02.420
You do quite
well for someone

07:02.420 --> 07:04.210
who doesn't like
to recite poetry.

07:04.210 --> 07:05.960
Oh, of course.

07:05.960 --> 07:08.960
The class will take a
ten-minute break to cool off.

